name: BUG - Multiple pipelines shown running since 17th December on Rundeck
text_content:
Issue - Multiple pipelines shown running since 17th December on Rundeck
Investigation Team - Data Engineering
Findings:
It was observed that Real Time Dashboards (Non-Marketing), which started around "2022-12-16T22:00:00Z", encountered the below error on its second last step-
Exception while executing step [1]: [java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Metaspace]
The above OOME metaspace error is related to the tomcat process, which is responsible for running the rundeck, and which was not able to load its respective classes into the metaspace and threw this error.

Now, when this error got thrown, this process was not able to update its status from the backend, because of which other jobs scheduled at that time were shown as queued or "scheduled to run", as found in their logs.

Since the statuses of these jobs in the queue when the issue happened weren't updated, their later runs did not execute. But the jobs that were scheduled to run later ran fine.

Also, when we checked for these jobs at the backend, we couldn't find any process running (as the frontend of rundeck showed them running for 3 days).

Thus, to conclude, the tomcat process responsible for running the rundeck encountered out of memory error for its metaspace, therefore unable to load classes, which led to the discrepancy in the status of the jobs running.
Corrective Action:
Killing the jobs shown as running and rerunning them helped resolve the issue

name: Set up a system/process for removing customer data from CCPA requests.
Fix Delivery/Fulfillment fields.
text_content:
Two issues we've noticed here, in order of priority below.  

In the core models (order_view, etc.): the field called ‘date_delivered’ currently is populated first by looking at shopify’s delivery information, then failing that, USPS delivery data.  However - when observing USPS delivery data, it appears that these models are simply pulling event dates from USPS regardless of their status in USPS, hence we have hundreds of undelivered orders marked as delivered based on event dates in USPS, when those dates are associated with non-delivery events.
Example of this occurring: order #1163945
Let me know if I've interpreted this correctly - I’ve established this based on code here: https://github.com/freshcleantees/analytics/blob/7e36080ed27ea0c947f3328e06211bbd8a98cd01/models/warehouse/core/final/order_view.sql
But essentially the call to USPS delivery data needs to be filtered for rows in which packages have actually been delivered, otherwise the ‘date_delivered’ field will continue to give a false sense of delivery outcomes.  Please let me know if you have questions or would like to discuss this.
It appears we might not be observing full delivery data.  There appear to be a large number of orders for which we can't observe deliveries in either Shopify or USPS.
Example orders: #1136575 (UPS); #1136745 (DHL)
Consider reading in notification data from Shopify, as it seems some of these might actually have delivery notifications sent out, despite not showing up as delivered in our current Shopify fulfillment table.
These orders were delivered, but this is not reflected in our Shopify ingestion ("RAW"."SHOPIFY"."FULFILLMENT") or USPS ("ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DELIVERY_USPS")

name: GA pipeline fix
text_content:
there’s an issue with our rundeck scheduling that I’m hoping you can help resolve.  Currently, the standard production modeling jobs are disabled, I imagine to make room for the ‘real time’ pipelines.

First priority: I cannot pull in any GA data for this weekend using any of our pipelines (GA pipeline, real-time marketing, etc.). We need to get our hands on those data, so it would be great if you could get those in as soon as you can upon login.

Broadly with regard to scheduling, the issue here is for marketing sources, when the ‘real-time’ marketing jobs are disabled:
 we don’t get weekend data for marketing sources whose pipelines are not set to run on weekends.  For example, the GA pipeline is affected by this (http://34.123.22.229:4440/project/FreshCleanTees-Pipelines/job/show/6fa3d081-ae8d-4d76-97b5-325f47a74d77)
it appears these weekend data, if they’re marketing related, are not modeled after they’re pulled in on Monday.
Hence, we have a bit of a hole in this design.  It would be great if the team could implement a short-term fix as soon as possible upon login on Tuesday, but then let’s discuss longer-term solutions during our meeting this week.  thanks! (edited)

-For non-U.S. domains, add a prefix to order number, based on the following codes:
https://www.worldstandards.eu/other/tlds/ (can add this as a seed data table in our warehouse)
-Bind non-U.S. observations to U.S. observations, this way we don't have any new tables and don't need new modeling logic.

https://fresh-clean-tees-ca.myshopify.com/

let me know if you need credentials in order to perform API pulls for this domain.  thanks!

name: Order Identification: Atidiv team to inherit my initial query and use it for testing with Sid.
text_content:
Here's what I'm thinking for identifying the set of delivered/out for delivery orders that will require updating in Shopify.  Please note the following:
The 'timediff' filter at the bottom will depend on the cadence of the overall pipeline.  If we are able to have the following steps completed in less than 12 hours, we can set this process to run more often, and hence set this value to a lower number:
Run+Model Skubana
Run+Model USPS Deliveries
(if needed) Run+Model the audit table which identifies orders that have already had their status updated (see#2).
We may want to add a pipeline+model that this query can check against, which identifies orders which already got updated so we avoid double-notifications.


--Delivered
with orders as (
  select order_number, created_at, ship_date, trackingnumber, shipping_carrier
  from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."SKUBANA_SHIPMENTS"
  where shipping_carrier like '%DHL%'),
  
deliveries as (
  select name as order_number, delivered, event, eventdatetime
  from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DELIVERY_USPS" 
)

select a.order_number, a.trackingnumber, b.eventdatetime, b.delivered
from orders a
left join deliveries b
on a.order_number=b.order_number
where delivered=TRUE and timediff(hour, eventdatetime, getdate())<=12


--Out for Delivery
--Out for Delivery
with orders as (
  select order_number, created_at, ship_date, trackingnumber, shipping_carrier
  from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."SKUBANA_SHIPMENTS"

name: Materialize a model for weekday click-to-deliver and click-to-ship times.
text_content:
This is to address the fact that the following query is slow and ideally would be run alongside our core models (instead of continuously when opening the relevant workbook):

with orders as (
  select 
  a.*,
  b.shipping_carrier
  from 
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_VIEW" a
  left join
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."SKUBANA_SHIPMENTS" b
  on a.name=b.order_number
  left join 
  (select date_actual::date as date_actual, 
   IS_BUSINESS_DAY
   from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DIM_DATE") c
  on a.created_at::date=c.date_actual::date
  where a.date_delivered is not null and a.shipdate is not null
),

click_to_deliver_weekdays as (
select order_number,
sum(case when is_business_day=TRUE then 1 else 0 end) as weekdays_click_to_deliver
from (
  select a.*,
  b.is_business_day
  from
  orders a
  left join 
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DIM_DATE" b
  on b.date_actual::date >= a.created_at::date
  and b.date_actual::date < a.date_delivered::date)
group by order_number),

click_to_ship_weekdays as (
select order_number,
sum(case when is_business_day=TRUE then 1 else 0 end) as weekdays_click_to_ship
from (
  select a.*,
  b.is_business_day
  from
  orders a
  left join 
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DIM_DATE" b
  on b.date_actual::date >= a.created_at::date
  and b.date_actual::date < a.shipdate::date)
group by order_number)

select a.*, 
b.weekdays_click_to_deliver,
c.weekdays_click_to_ship
from orders a
left join
click_to_deliver_weekdays b
on a.order_number=b.order_number
left join
click_to_ship_weekdays c
on a.order_number=c.order_number

name: System for updating fulfilment out-for-delivery or delivered in Shopify
text_content:
The goal here is to fill in a gap in our email touch-points for DHL packages - these packages don't automatically get a delivery notification sent through Shopify.  The goal is to do the following, several times a day: 
(1) pull delivered DHL packages per our existing USPS pipeline
(2) push the associated customer emails to Klaviyo into a 'Package Delivered' campaign
(3) send out the Package Delivered campaign to these emails 

It appears that Klaviyo  allows us to perform steps #2-3 through their API, which means we could automate this system in house.  However, it's possible I'm oversimplifying here, so would be great to have a discussion about this.

Relevant API Documentation: 
Populate list of recipients: https://apidocs.klaviyo.com/reference/lists-segments
Send campaign: https://apidocs.klaviyo.com/reference/campaigns#send-campaign

name: Update COGS mapping for "PPK" SKUs
text_content:
Hi team,

Our COGS mapping needs to be updated to properly account for some missing SKUS.  It appears that the missing COGS data is for "pre-pack" SKUs in the core models.  I think the fix should be rather simple, as the relevant COGS data appears to be present in SKUBANA already.

In particular:
The set of Pre-Pack SKUs that need COGS mapped on can be identified as follows:

  select distinct sku
  from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW"
  where cogs is null
  and child_sku like '%PPK%'

The relevant COGS information appears to be available per Skubana, based on the following query:

select * from "RAW"."SKUBANA"."_SNAPSHOT_COGS"
where internalsku in (
    select distinct sku
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW"
    where cogs is null
    and child_sku like '%PPK%'
 )

But for some reason these data aren't getting joined on in our core models.  I think this should be an easy modeling update, but let me know if you run into issues / would like to discuss.

Another note: these are packs, but with only one child sku - this is because they're 'pre-packed', meaning not made up of individual tees, so the packs should be just a single row in ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW.

Another note: these are packs, but with only one child sku - this is because they're 'pre-packed', meaning not made up of individual tees, so the packs should be just a single row in ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW.

name: Help QC/optimize a query relating to inventory and OOS rates by product.
text_content:
Dashboard for review: 
https://app.sigmacomputing.com/freshcleantees/workbook/workbook-68WeeLOw7Az1EACsvtkPmO

Underlying Query:
with inventory as (
  select inventory_snapshot_date, product_mastersku, 
  case when product_name like '%Tall%' then regexp_replace(product_name, ' Crew Neck$', '') else product_name end as product_name,
  sum(quantity) as quantity
  from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."INVENTORY"
  group by inventory_snapshot_date, product_mastersku, product_name
),

size_mix as (
 select *,
  sum(net_sales) over 
  	(partition by 
     sku_size_agnostic, macro_category, sub_category) as product_sales,
  case when product_sales>0 then net_sales/product_sales else 0 end as size_mix
  from (
	select 
    macro_category,
    sub_category,
    child_sku,
    regexp_replace(child_sku, '-(S|M|L|XL|2XL|3XL|MT|LT|XLT|2XLT|3XLT)$', '') as sku_size_agnostic,
    sum(net_sales) as net_sales
    from (
    	select a.* from
      	"ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW" a
      	left join 
      	inventory b
      	on a.created_at::date=b.inventory_snapshot_date::date 
      		and a.child_sku= b.product_mastersku
      	where b.quantity>25 and datediff(day, created_at::date, current_date()::date)<=90
    )
    group by 
    macro_category, sub_category, sku_size_agnostic, child_sku)
),

daily_product_sales as (
    select 
    created_at::date as created_at,
    child_sku as sku,
    sum(net_sales) as net_sales,
    sum(return) as return
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW" 
    group by created_at::date, child_sku
),

daily_total_sales as (
   select 
    created_at::date as created_at,
    sum(net_sales) as net_sales_total,
    sum(return) as return_total
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW" 
    group by created_at::date
),

sales as (
  select
  child_sku as sku,
  regexp_replace(child_sku, '-(S|M|L|XL|2XL|3XL|MT|LT|XLT|2XLT|3XLT)$', '') as sku_size_agnostic,
  sum(case when datediff(day,created_at::date, getdate())<=90 then quantity else 0 end) as quantity_sold_last90days,
  max(case when quantity=0 then NULL else quantity end) as quantity_max,
  avg(case when quantity=0 then NULL else quantity end) as quantity_avg,
  avg(case when quantity=0 then NULL else net_sales end) as net_sales_avg,
  median(case when quantity=0 then NULL else quantity end) as quantity_median,
  stddev(case when quantity=0 then NULL else quantity end) as quantity_sd
  from (
    select
    created_at::date as created_at,
    child_sku,
    sum(child_sku_quantity) as quantity,
    sum(net_sales) as net_sales
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW" 
    where created_at NOT between '2020-11-27' and '2020-11-30'
    and created_at NOT between '2019-11-29' and '2019-12-02'
    and datediff(day,created_at::date, getdate())<365.25
    group by created_at::date, child_sku
    order by quantity desc
  )
  group by sku, sku_size_agnostic
  order by quantity_max desc
),

sales_size_agnostic as (
  select
  sku_size_agnostic,
  sum(case when datediff(day,created_at::date, getdate())<=90 then quantity else 0 end) as size_agnostic_quantity_sold_last90days
  from (
    select
    created_at::date as created_at,
    sku_size_agnostic,
    sum(child_sku_quantity) as quantity
    from  (
        select *,
        regexp_replace(child_sku, '-(S|M|L|XL|2XL|3XL|MT|LT|XLT|2XLT|3XLT)$', '') as sku_size_agnostic
        from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW")
    where created_at NOT between '2020-11-27' and '2020-11-30'
    and created_at NOT between '2019-11-29' and '2019-12-02'
    and datediff(day,created_at::date, getdate())<365.25
    group by created_at::date, sku_size_agnostic
    order by quantity desc
  )
  group by sku_size_agnostic
),

mapping as (
    select 
    sku, 
    product_id,
    product_title,
    size, 
    macro_category,
    subcategory,
    macro_color, 
    color
    from "RAW"."GOOGLE_SHEET_SCHEMA"."PRODUCT_MAPPING"
    where product_title not ilike '%test%' and product_title not ilike '%auto%renew' and product_title not ilike '%gift card%'
)

select a.*, 
b.*, 
c.quantity_max, c.quantity_avg, c.quantity_median, c.quantity_sd, c.quantity_sold_last90days, c.net_sales_avg,
d.size_agnostic_quantity_sold_last90days,
e.net_sales, e.return,
f.net_sales_total, f.return_total,
g.size_mix
from 
inventory a
left join 
mapping b
on a.PRODUCT_MASTERSKU = b.SKU
left join 
sales c
on a.PRODUCT_MASTERSKU=c.sku
left join 
sales_size_agnostic d
on c.sku_size_agnostic=d.sku_size_agnostic
left join 
daily_product_sales e
on a.product_mastersku=e.sku and a.inventory_snapshot_date=e.created_at
left join 
daily_total_sales f
on a.inventory_snapshot_date=f.created_at
left join 
size_mix g
on a.product_mastersku=g.child_sku and b.macro_category=g.macro_category and b.subcategory=g.sub_category

name: Assist with optimizing a query to count business days between order placement and shipment/delivery.
text_content:
Query needing optimization:

with orders as (
  select 
  a.*,
  b.shipping_carrier
  from 
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_VIEW" a
  left join
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."SKUBANA_SHIPMENTS" b
  on a.name=b.order_number
  left join 
  (select date_actual::date as date_actual, 
   IS_BUSINESS_DAY
   from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DIM_DATE") c
  on a.created_at::date=c.date_actual::date
  where a.date_delivered is not null and a.shipdate is not null
),

click_to_deliver_weekdays as (
select order_number,
sum(case when is_business_day=TRUE then 1 else 0 end) as weekdays_click_to_deliver
from (
  select a.*,
  b.is_business_day
  from
  orders a
  left join 
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DIM_DATE" b
  on b.date_actual::date >= a.created_at::date
  and b.date_actual::date < a.date_delivered::date)
group by order_number),

click_to_ship_weekdays as (
select order_number,
sum(case when is_business_day=TRUE then 1 else 0 end) as weekdays_click_to_ship
from (
  select a.*,
  b.is_business_day
  from
  orders a
  left join 
  "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DIM_DATE" b
  on b.date_actual::date >= a.created_at::date
  and b.date_actual::date < a.shipdate::date)
group by order_number)

select a.*, 
b.weekdays_click_to_deliver,
c.weekdays_click_to_ship
from orders a
left join
click_to_deliver_weekdays b
on a.order_number=b.order_number
left join
click_to_ship_weekdays c
on a.order_number=c.order_number

name: Explore possibility of designing a small set of dashboards with 'real-time' update functionality available within the dashboard itself
Investigate what appear to be discrepancies in the CHILD_SKU_QUANTITY and PARENT_SKU_QUANTITY_RATIO columns of ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW
text_content: Take for example, Order #459856.  This order was for one All-White 5-Pack.  In "ORDER_LINE_SKUBANA_VIEW" this order takes up one row: since it only involves one Child SKU.  The 'Child Sku Quantity' field reflects 5, which is correct.  But what I don't fully understand is why the 'Parent Sku Quantity Ratio' field reflects 0.5.  My expectation would be that this field equals 0.2, such that 'Child Sku Quantity'  * 'Parent Sku Quantity' = 1, or 5 * 0.2 = 1.  As it stands, this value is equal to 2.5, which would suggest 2.5 All-White 5-Packs were ordered.  Let me know if I'm misunderstanding something and when you're available to discuss these fields.

text_content:
Hi team,

The idea here is to generate a maximally user-facing marketing model that allows for analysis at a potentially quite granular level.  The relevant dimensions for this model are:

Day-Funnel-Creative-Campaign-Adset-Ad-Platform

The relevant metrics and a prototype FB structure for this can be found in my query below (Which supports some ad-hoc Sigma objects) currently.  

Please feel free to grab some time on my calendar for us to discuss.

Thanks!


with date_master as (
    Select *
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."DIM_DATE"
),
sales as (
    Select *
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDER_VIEW"
),
daily_sales as (
    Select processed_at::date as date_start,
        --processed_at::date-1 as prev_day, 
        sum(coalesce(net_sales, 0)+coalesce(shipping, 0)) as net_sales,
        sum(coalesce(discounts, 0)) as discount,
        sum(coalesce(gross_sales, 0)) as gross_sales,
        sum(coalesce(taxes, 0)) as tax,
        sum(coalesce(SHIPPING, 0)) as shipping,
        sum(coalesce(cogs, 0)) as cogs,
        sum(coalesce(cost_of_shipping, 0)) as cost_of_shipping,
        sum(coalesce(cost_of_fulfillment, 0)) as cost_of_fulfillment,
        sum(coalesce(return, 0)) as return,
        count(distinct case when created_at::date=first_purchase_at::date then customer_id end) as new_customers,
        count(distinct case when created_at::date<>first_purchase_at::date then customer_id end) as return_customers,
        count(distinct order_number) as orders
    from sales
    group by 1
    order by 1 desc
),
facebook_insight as (
    Select *
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."INSIGHT_AD"
),
facebook_revenue as (
    Select *
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."INSIGHT_AD_ACTION_VALUES"
),
facebook_actions as (
    Select *
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."INSIGHT_AD_ACTIONS"
),
facebook_campaigns as (
    Select
    distinct id as campaign_id,
    name as campaign_name
    from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."CAMPAIGN"
),
facebook_metrics_ad_level as (
    Select 
    a.ad_id,
    a.ad_name,
    a.ad_set_name as adset_name,
    a.campaign_name,
    a.date_start::date as date_start,
    a.date_stop::date as date_stop,
    sum(coalesce(a.impressions, 0)) as impressions,
    sum(coalesce(a.spend, 0)) as spend,
    sum(coalesce(a.reach, 0)) as reach,
    sum(coalesce(a.unique_clicks,0)) as unique_clicks,
    sum(coalesce(a.clicks,0)) as clicks
    from facebook_insight a
    --left join facebook_campaigns b
    --on a.campaign_id=b.campaign_id
    group by ad_id, ad_name, adset_name, campaign_name, date_start, date_stop 
),
facebook_actions_ad_level as (
    Select 
    ad_id,
    date_start::date as date_start,
    date_stop::date as date_stop,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_purchase' then value else 0 end) as purchases,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_purchase' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0)+coalesce(aw_1d_view,0) else 0 end) as purchases_7d_click_1d_view,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_purchase' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0) else 0 end) as purchases_7d_click,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_initiated_checkout' then value else 0 end) as ci,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_initiated_checkout' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0)+coalesce(aw_1d_view,0) else 0 end) as ci_7d_click_1d_view,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_initiated_checkout' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0) else 0 end) as ci_7d_click,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_add_to_cart' then value else 0 end) as atc,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_add_to_cart' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0)+coalesce(aw_1d_view,0) else 0 end) as atc_7d_click_1d_view,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_add_to_cart' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0) else 0 end) as atc_7d_click,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='link_click' then value else 0 end) as link_clicks,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='link_click' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0)+coalesce(aw_1d_view,0) else 0 end) as link_clicks_7d_click_1d_view,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='link_click' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0) else 0 end) as link_clicks_7d_click
    from  facebook_actions
    group by ad_id, date_start, date_stop
),
facebook_action_values_ad_level as (
    Select 
    ad_id,
    date_start::date as date_start,
    date_stop::date as date_stop,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_purchase' then value else 0 end) as revenue,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_purchase' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0)+coalesce(aw_1d_view,0) else 0 end) as revenue_7d_click_1d_view,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_purchase' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0) else 0 end) as revenue_7d_click,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_initiated_checkout' then value else 0 end) as ci_value,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_initiated_checkout' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0)+coalesce(aw_1d_view,0) else 0 end) as ci_value_7d_click_1d_view,
  	sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_initiated_checkout' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0) else 0 end) as ci_value_7d_click,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_add_to_cart' then value else 0 end) as atc_value,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_add_to_cart' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0)+coalesce(aw_1d_view,0) else 0 end) as atc_value_7d_click_1d_view,
    sum(case when ACTION_TYPE='omni_add_to_cart' then coalesce(aw_7d_click,0) else 0 end) as atc_value_7d_click
    from  facebook_revenue
    group by 1, 2, 3
)

select 
*,
case when spend_fb>0 then revenue_fb/spend_fb else null end as roas_fb,
case when atc_fb>0 then spend_fb/atc_fb else null end as cpatc_fb,
case when ci_fb>0 then spend_fb/ci_fb else null end as cpci_fb,

case when spend_fb>0 then revenue_fb_7d_click_1d_view/spend_fb else null end as roas_fb_7d_click_1d_view,
case when atc_fb_7d_click_1d_view>0 then spend_fb/atc_fb_7d_click_1d_view else null end as cpatc_fb_7d_click_1d_view,
case when ci_fb_7d_click_1d_view>0 then spend_fb/ci_fb_7d_click_1d_view else null end as cpci_fb_7d_click_1d_view,

case when spend_fb>0 then revenue_fb_7d_click/spend_fb else null end as roas_fb_7d_click,
case when atc_fb_7d_click>0 then spend_fb/atc_fb_7d_click else null end as cpatc_fb_7d_click,
case when ci_fb_7d_click>0 then spend_fb/ci_fb_7d_click else null end as cpci_fb_7d_click,

sum(new_customers) over (partition by extract(month from date_start)) as new_customers_monthly,
sum(return_customers) over (partition by extract(month from date_start)) as return_customers_monthly,
sum(net_sales) over (partition by extract(month from date_start)) as net_sales_monthly,
sum(spend_fb) over (partition by extract(month from date_start)) as spend_fb_monthly
from (
    select
    b.date_start,
    c.date_stop,
    b.new_customers,
    b.return_customers,
    b.net_sales,
    b.shipping,
    b.orders,
    c.ad_id,
    c.ad_name,
    c.adset_name,
    c.campaign_name,
    c.impressions as impressions_fb,
    c.spend as spend_fb,
    c.reach as reach_fb,
  	c.unique_clicks as unique_clicks_fb,
    c.clicks as clicks_fb,
    d.purchases as purchases_fb,
    d.purchases_7d_click_1d_view as purchases_fb_7d_click_1d_view,
  	d.purchases_7d_click as purchases_fb_7d_click,
    d.ci as ci_fb,
  	d.ci_7d_click_1d_view as ci_fb_7d_click_1d_view,
  	d.ci_7d_click as ci_fb_7d_click,
    d.atc as atc_fb,
  	d.atc_7d_click_1d_view as atc_fb_7d_click_1d_view,
  	d.atc_7d_click as atc_fb_7d_click,
    d.link_clicks as link_clicks_fb,
  	d.link_clicks_7d_click_1d_view as link_clicks_fb_7d_click_1d_view,
  	d.link_clicks_7d_click as link_clicks_fb_7d_click,
    e.revenue as revenue_fb,
  	e.revenue_7d_click_1d_view as revenue_fb_7d_click_1d_view,
  	e.revenue_7d_click as revenue_fb_7d_click
    from 
    (select * from daily_sales) b
    LEFT JOIN
    (select * from facebook_metrics_ad_level) c
    ON b.date_start=c.date_start
    LEFT JOIN
    (select * from facebook_actions_ad_level) d
    on c.ad_id=d.ad_id and c.date_start=d.date_start and c.date_stop=d.date_stop
    LEFT JOIN
    (select * from facebook_action_values_ad_level) e
    on c.ad_id=e.ad_id and c.date_start=e.date_start and c.date_stop=e.date_stop)
where extract(year from date_start)>2019 and date_start<=getdate()
order by date_start desc, spend_fb desc

name: Investigate duplicate rows in YOTPO_REVIEWS
text_content:
We were alerted of 16 records with duplicate id as shown by the query below.
select * from "PC_FIVETRAN_DB"."YOTPO"."YOTPO_REVIEWS"
where id in (
  select id
  from "PC_FIVETRAN_DB"."YOTPO"."YOTPO_REVIEWS"
  group by 1
  having count(*) > 1
)
order by id 
Looking at the records, all columns are the same for duplicate rows except for the UPDATED_AT column. Interestingly, a lot of the duplicate rows were from the same email.

Could you please do an RCA and try find out why this duplication occurred?

Solved by doing a historical resync.

Any client driver version lower than what is listed below will be out of support as of July 31st, 2021 based on the Snowflake Support policy.

Snowflake SnowSQL 1.2.0

Snowflake JDBC Driver 3.9.2

Snowflake Node.JS Driver 1.3.1

Please upgrade all drivers to the latest versions to take advantage of important fixes and enhancements to security, performance, and other functions. 

Snowflake will not be able to assist with any issues related to versions that are out of support.

To check the driver version in use, we have added a new feature to view the driver version information in the Query History tab under the Client Info column. 

If you have any questions related to driver upgrades, please submit a support case for assistance referencing this email.

name: Identify ways to improve runtime of dbt models (e.g., reduce the time it takes to run hourly/daily/full refresh jobs)
Move all "standard" transformations to an "_01_std_transform" model for all dbt models
text_content:
Let's identify the "standard" transformations we perform on all data, and for every model, create a new [MODEL NAME]_01_std_transform.sql model (e.g., shopify_orders_01_std_transform.

These "standard" transformations should include, but are not limited to:
1. Converting timezones to PST if not already in PST.
2. Removing the timezone stamp from timestamps (e.g., first convert to PST, then make the field a timestamp without timezone field)
3. Convert non-USD monetary amounts to USD (keep original column).
4. Lowercase and trim email addresses.
5. Uppercase and trim product SKUs.
6. Uppercase and trim discount/coupon codes.
7. Dedupe records (where relevant).

if: channel not in ('instagram-ad-comment','instagram-comment','facebook','facebook-comment') and tag_id in (238951,289765)

if: channel in ('instagram-ad-comment','instagram-comment','facebook','facebook-comment') and tag_id in (238951,289765)

name: Investigate the Recharge API and determine if we can accurately pull subscriptions
text_content:
Context:

Recharge does not always change the updated_at field on records in the subscriptions model (in their database), thus Fivetran does not always pick up incremental updates to subscriptions.
This is a less than ideal solution, because often subscriptions are updated in Recharge but not synced by Fivetran due to the aforementioned issue.

Objective:

Explore the Recharge API and see if we can develop a pipeline that accurately pulls subscriptions into a table in Snowflake that matches the Fivetran table structure.
This pipeline will need to pull the complete data set and be updated incrementally, including new subscriptions and changes to existing subscriptions.

Other Notes:

@aabbeirroy Will be the primary point of contact on this project.

name: Investigate the Recharge API and determine if we can (accurately) pull charges and charge line items
text_content:
Context:

Fivetran says that the Recharge API has integrity issues, so they rely on webhooks to update the PC_FIVETRAN_DB.RECHARGE.CHARGE and PC_FIVETRAN_DB.RECHARGE.CHARGE_LINE_ITEM tables.
This is a less than ideal solution, because we do not have historical information about charges / charge line items (that occurred before the last historical sync).
In particular, most of the custom property fields (e.g., the fulfillment scent fields) are NULL, and when we check those records in the Recharge app, they are not null.

Objective:

Explore the Recharge API and see if we can develop a pipeline that accurately pulls charges and charge line items into tables in Snowflake that match the Fivetran table structures.
This pipeline will need to pull the complete data set and be updated incrementally, including new charges and charge line items and changes to existing subscriptions.

Other Notes:

@aabbeirroy Will be the primary point of contact on this project.

name: Why is count(*) group by not summing properly?
text_content:
There are 1,336 rows but this group by count(*) shows the output as 853 and 482 - the sum is 1,335

WITH a AS (
  SELECT order_id, processed_at, email, SPLIT_PART(SHIPPING_ADDRESS_ZIP, '-', 1) AS zip, SUM(net_sales) AS total_net_sales
  FROM ANALYTICS.MODELED_DATA.ORDER_LINE_COMBINED
  GROUP BY 1, 2, 3, 4
),

b AS (
  SELECT a.*, TRIM(cust.shipping_address_first_name) AS first_name, TRIM(cust.shipping_address_last_name) AS last_name, 
    CONCAT(first_name, ' ', last_name) AS buyer_name
  FROM a
  LEFT JOIN (
    SELECT DISTINCT(shopify_order_id), shipping_address_first_name, shipping_address_last_name
    FROM ANALYTICS.MODELED_DATA.CUSTOMER_ORDERS
  ) cust ON cust.shopify_order_id = a.order_id
),

c AS (
  SELECT b.email, b.buyer_name, LISTAGG(DISTINCT(b.zip), '; ') AS op_zip, MIN(processed_at) AS first_op_purch, MAX(processed_at) AS last_op_purch, 
    SUM(b.total_net_sales) AS total_net_sales, COUNT(DISTINCT b.order_id) AS total_orders
  FROM b
  GROUP BY 1, 2
),

d AS (
  SELECT c.*, amz.*
  FROM c
  LEFT JOIN (
    SELECT buyername AS amz_name, LISTAGG(DISTINCT(SPLIT_PART(shippingaddress_postalcode, '-', 1)), '; ') AS amz_zip,
        MIN(purchasedate) AS first_amz_purch, MAX(purchasedate) AS last_amz_purch, 
        COUNT(DISTINCT(AMAZONORDERID)) AS amz_orders, SUM(ordertotal_amount) AS amz_order_total
    FROM "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."AMAZON_ORDER"
    WHERE purchasedate >= '2021-07-01'
    GROUP BY 1
  ) AS amz ON amz.amz_name = c.buyer_name
),

e AS (
  SELECT *, 
    CASE WHEN first_op_purch < first_amz_purch THEN 'OP' ELSE 'AMZ' END AS first_purch_platform, 
    CASE WHEN last_op_purch < last_amz_purch THEN 'AMZ' ELSE 'OP' END AS last_purch_platform
  FROM d
  WHERE amz_orders IS NOT NULL AND (CONTAINS(amz_zip, op_zip) OR CONTAINS(op_zip, amz_zip))
) 

select distinct last_purch_platform, count(*) 
from e 
group by 1

text_content:
with pulled_orders as (
  select 
    so.id as shopify_order_id,
    so.processed_at shopify_order_date,  
    dateadd(hour,DAYS_TO_SHIP*24,SHOPIFY_ORDER_DATE)  as ship_date,
    qbo.ORDER_KEY,
    qbo.DELIVER_DATE,
    qbo.PROCESSED,
    qbo.DELIVERED,
    qbo.CARRIER_SCANNED,
    qbo.CONFIRMED,
    qbo.BACK_ORDERED,
    qbo.CANCELLED_RATE,
    qbo.CANCELLATIONS,
    qbo.SHIPMENTS,
    qbo.ITEM_QUANTITY,
    qbo.DAYS_TO_ALLOCATE,
    qbo.DAYS_TO_BACKORDER,
    qbo.DAYS_TO_SCAN,  
    qbo.DAYS_TO_PROCESS,
    qbo.DAYS_TO_CONFIRM,
    qbo.DAYS_TO_SHIP,
    qbo.CALENDAR_DAYS_IN_TRANSIT,
    qbo.CALENDAR_DAYS_TO_DELIVER,
    coalesce(qbo.CARRIER_PROVIDER, tplo.ROUTING_INFO_CARRIER) as carrier,
    coalesce(qbo.SHIPPING_PROFILE_NAME,tplo.ROUTING_INFO_MODE) as carrier_mode,
    case when tplo.FACILITY_IDENTIFIER_NAME = 'QuickBox ATL' then 'ATLANTA' else 'DENVER' end as shipping_faclity,
    tplo.SHIP_TO_ZIP as DESTINATION_ZIP,
    left(tplo.SHIP_TO_ZIP,3) as DESTINATION_ZIP3,
    tplo.SHIP_TO_COUNTRY, 
    tplo.REFERENCE_NUM  
  from "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."ORDERS" so
  left join "RAW"."THREE_PL"."_SNAPSHOT_ORDERS" tplo on so.name = concat('#',tplo.REFERENCE_NUM::VARCHAR)
  left join "RAW"."QUICKBOX"."DELIVERY_INFO"  qbo on tplo.ORDER_ID::INTEGER = replace(qbo.ORDER_KEY,'"','')
 -- PROCESSED.QUICKBOX.STG_QUICKBOX_DELIVERY_INFO 
  where REFERENCE_NUM is not NULL
  and qbo.ORDER_KEY is not NULL
  order by SHOPIFY_ORDER_DATE asc 
),

orders AS (
  SELECT date, orders
  FROM ANALYTICS.MODELED_DATA.DAILY_AGG_SALES
  ORDER BY 1 DESC
  ),
  
base as (
  select a.CREATED_DATE::date date, a.ORDER_KEY,
  case when a.CANCELLATIONS::integer = 1 then 0
    when (a.DELIVER_DATE::VARCHAR <> '0000-00-00' and a.DELIVER_DATE::VARCHAR is not NULL) then 7 
    when (a.SCAN_DATE::VARCHAR <> '0000-00-00' and a.SCAN_DATE::VARCHAR is not NULL) then 5 
    when (a.CONFIRMED_DATE::VARCHAR <> '0000-00-00' and a.CONFIRMED_DATE::VARCHAR is not NULL) then 4 
    when (a.PROCESS_DATE::VARCHAR <> '0000-00-00' and a.PROCESS_DATE::VARCHAR is not NULL) then 3 
    when (a.ALLOCATED_DATE::VARCHAR <> '0000-00-00' and a.ALLOCATED_DATE::VARCHAR is not NULL) then 2 
    else 1 end as status,
  case when b.FACILITY_IDENTIFIER_NAME = 'QuickBox ATL' then 'ATLANTA' else 'DENVER' end as warehouse
  from "RAW"."QUICKBOX"."CREATED_INFO" a
  left join "ANALYTICS"."MODELED_DATA"."THREE_PL_ORDERS" b
  on a.order_key::number=b.order_id::number
),

confirmed_orders AS (
  select date, status as sort_helper, warehouse,
  case when status =0 then 'Cancelled'
    when status =1 then 'Created'
    when status =2 then 'Allocated'
    when status =3 then 'Processed'
    when status =4 then 'Confirmed'
    when status =5 then 'Scanned'
    when status =7 then 'Delivered'
    end as status, 
  count(status) orders 
  from base
  where sort_helper = 4
  group by 1,2,3 order by 1 desc, 2 desc
)

select o.*, p.pulled_orders, c.confirmed_orders
from orders o
LEFT JOIN (SELECT shopify_order_date::date as order_date, count(distinct shopify_order_id) AS pulled_orders
           FROM pulled_orders
           GROUP BY 1
           ORDER BY 1 DESC) p ON p.order_date = o.date
LEFT JOIN (SELECT date, SUM(orders) AS confirmed_orders
           FROM confirmed_orders
           GROUP BY 1
           ORDER BY 1 DESC) c ON c.date = o.date

Active subscriptions w/ no recent orders
text_content:
The query below shows all sub IDs that are considered active subscriptions and where the last order date was before March 1st 2022. Can we pull more fields/data from Recharge that can help explain what is going on here?

SELECT *
FROM (
  SELECT DISTINCT(subscription_id), MAX(processed_at) OVER (PARTITION BY subscription_id) AS last_order, 
    LAST_VALUE(frequency) OVER (PARTITION BY subscription_id ORDER BY processed_at DESC) AS last_order_freq
  FROM ANALYTICS.MODELED_DATA.ORDER_LINE_COMBINED
  WHERE subs_created_date IS NOT NULL AND subs_cancelled_date IS NULL) 
WHERE last_order < '2022-03-01'

The query below shows all sub IDs that are considered active subscriptions and where the last order date was before March 1st 2022. Can we pull more fields/data from Recharge that can help explain what is going on here?

SELECT *
FROM (
  SELECT DISTINCT(subscription_id), MAX(processed_at) OVER (PARTITION BY subscription_id) AS last_order, 
    LAST_VALUE(frequency) OVER (PARTITION BY subscription_id ORDER BY processed_at DESC) AS last_order_freq
  FROM ANALYTICS.MODELED_DATA.ORDER_LINE_COMBINED
  WHERE subs_created_date IS NOT NULL AND subs_cancelled_date IS NULL) 
WHERE last_order < '2022-03-01'

name: Multiple emails for certain subscription IDs
text_content:
Query showing multiple email addresses for sub IDs. How do these get treated in the order line model?
SELECT DISTINCT subscription_id, email 
FROM ANALYTICS.MODELED_DATA.ORDER_LINE_COMBINED
WHERE subscription_id IN (
  SELECT subscription_id
  FROM (
    SELECT subscription_id, email, row_number() over (PARTITION BY subscription_id ORDER BY email DESC) AS row_number
    FROM ANALYTICS.MODELED_DATA.ORDER_LINE_COMBINED
    GROUP BY 1, 2
  ) WHERE row_number > 1
) 
ORDER BY 1 DESC

name: Partner data report for april 2020
text_content:
Report query : 

{code:sql}
SELECT 
	yl.`reportDate` AS 'Date',
	a.code AS 'EmpID',
	a.name AS 'AgentName',
	COUNT( DISTINCT yc.`yelpListingId`) AS 'Partner Listings Processed',
	COUNT( DISTINCT CASE WHEN yc.change_type_Id=3 THEN yc.`yelpListingId` ELSE NULL END) AS 'NBA Partner Listings Processed',
	COUNT( DISTINCT CASE WHEN yc.source_Id=63 THEN yc.`yelpListingId` ELSE NULL END)  AS 'Partner AppleRap Listings Processed'	
FROM yelpListing yl
	LEFT JOIN agents a ON a.id=yl.`agentID` AND yl.listtype IS NULL AND yl.yelpCountryId=91
	LEFT JOIN `yelp_change/action` yc ON yl.id=yc.`yelpListingId`
		AND yc.source_type_id=4
WHERE yl.`reportDate` BETWEEN '2020-04-01' AND '2020-04-07'	
GROUP BY 1,2,3 
ORDER BY 1;{code}

Report query : 

{code:sql}
SELECT 
	yl.`reportDate` AS 'Date',
	a.code AS 'EmpID',
	a.name AS 'AgentName',
	COUNT( DISTINCT yc.`yelpListingId`) AS 'Partner Listings Processed',
	COUNT( DISTINCT CASE WHEN yc.change_type_Id=3 THEN yc.`yelpListingId` ELSE NULL END) AS 'NBA Partner Listings Processed',
	COUNT( DISTINCT CASE WHEN yc.source_Id=63 THEN yc.`yelpListingId` ELSE NULL END)  AS 'Partner AppleRap Listings Processed'	
FROM yelpListing yl
	LEFT JOIN agents a ON a.id=yl.`agentID` AND yl.listtype IS NULL AND yl.yelpCountryId=91
	LEFT JOIN `yelp_change/action` yc ON yl.id=yc.`yelpListingId`
		AND yc.source_type_id=4
WHERE yl.`reportDate` BETWEEN '2020-04-01' AND '2020-04-07'	
GROUP BY 1,2,3

name: Razor pages and MVC
text_content:
Razor is built on same infrastructure as mvc
When request comes same mvc infrastructure is used
If you are familiar with mvc then keep using it
If you are new dev then go for razor
Both are built on same technology, equally flexible
No technical limitations of one over the other

Razor pages makes it simple and quick to develop page-based applications. Razor Pages automatically implement antiforgery validation, which protects against cross-site request forgery (XSRF/CSRF) attacks. 

Razor Pages shines in smaller, “action” based web applications. For larger CRUD applications, MVC could still a great fit.

Retention % Reports for US and UK
text_content:
We want to create a report where we can look at a Retention curve so we need to calculate the following KPIs. We can use the same definition that we have in the US and UK Monthly Scorecards, but just change the time period.

Retention % (1 Months)
Retention % (2 Months)
Retention % (3 Months)
Retention % (4 Months)
Retention % (5 Months)
Retention % (6 Months)
Retention % (7 Months)
Retention % (8 Months)
Retention % (9 Months)
Retention % (10 Months)
Retention % (11 Months)
Retention % (12 Months)
Retention % (15 Months)
Retention % (18 Months)
Retention % (21 Months)
Retention % (24 Months)

We need to set this up so we can look at this for different reporting months, i.e, Monthly. For example for the reporting month of  Oct 2022 we would go back to Sept 30, 2020 as the start date for the Retention % (24 Months), but for reporting month of Sept 2022 we would go back to Aug 31, 2020 as the start date for the Retention % (24 Months). 

The farthest we would look back is June 30, 2020, so for reporting month Dec 2021, we would only report out on retention up to Retention % (18 Months).

Let's set this up so that we look at this monthly starting with Oct 2020 which will also allow us to set up a MOM comparison dashboard.

I think it will be easiest to QA if we set up an initial view with counts of Members at the beginning of the time period and Members remaining at the end of the time period because then we calculate Retention % by (Members remaining at the end of the time period) / (Members at the start of the time period). 

Also, we will eventually want to look at this by clinic as well as membership category, so I know our Retention % (3 Months) query is currently set up to look at the data by clinic, but I don't believe we have the ability to do so by membership category, so we should structure the query so that we can eventually look at the data both by clinic as well as membership category.

headers_2 = {'Authorization':'apikey 49e0955448e3402b81bd09b1ccec8cb7','Content-Type':'application/json'}
SCOPES = ['https://www.googleapis.com/auth/spreadsheets']
SPREADSHEET_ID = '14QB0HxZuH2Y_0vS8KGZfE7CtnnG0bn_uxps_MG-E4b4'
invalid_refer_text = 'referral_source_id'

def logger(msg,log_sheet=None):
    output = '{time}:{msg}'.format(time=datetime.now().astimezone(pytz.timezone('US/Pacific')).strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S PST'),msg=msg)
    print(output)
    if log_sheet is not None:
        result = sheet.values().append(
            spreadsheetId=SPREADSHEET_ID, range='Logger!A1',
            valueInputOption='USER_ENTERED', body={'values':[[output]]}
            ).execute()
        logger(result)

def initialize():
    creds = None
    if os.path.exists('token.pickle'):
        with open('token.pickle', 'rb') as token:
            creds = pickle.load(token)

    if not creds or not creds.valid:
        if creds and creds.expired and creds.refresh_token:
            creds.refresh(Request())
        else:
            flow = InstalledAppFlow.from_client_secrets_file(
                'credentials.json', SCOPES)
            creds = flow.run_local_server(port=0)
        # Save the credentials for the next run
        with open('token.pickle', 'wb') as token:
            pickle.dump(creds, token)

    service = build('sheets', 'v4', credentials=creds)
    sheet = service.spreadsheets()
    return sheet

def update_zeonti_customer(c_id,tags):
    tags = tags.split('|')
    """ get current customer info"""
    url = api_url + f'guests/{c_id}?expand=tags&expand=address_info&expand=preferences&expand=referral&expand=primary_employee'
    response = requests.get(url,headers=headers)
    response_json = response.json()

    """ copy response to new variable and add tags """
    upload_json = response_json.copy()
    try:
        if upload_json['tags'] is None:
            upload_json['tags'] = tags
        else:
            upload_json['tags'] = list(set(upload_json['tags'] + tags))
    except:
        print("Something went wrong")


    nested_update(upload_json, key='country_code', value='225',in_place=True)


    """ upload modified customer details back to zenoti"""
    upload_json_dmp = json.dumps(upload_json)


    response_update = requests.put(url,headers=headers_2,data=upload_json_dmp)

    if invalid_refer_text in response_update.text:
        upload_json['referral']['referral_source']['id'] = ['aa128923-2d0e-47a5-bbf7-8914ecbc833c']
        upload_json['referral']['referral_source']['name'] = ['Other']
        upload_json_dmp =json.dumps(upload_json)
        response_update = requests.put(url,headers=headers_2,data=upload_json_dmp)



    """ process will fail is mandatory fields are currently blank in Zenoti """


    if response_update.status_code != 200:
        return False,None,response_update.text


    updated_json = response_update.json()
    updated_tags = updated_json['tags']
    return response_update.status_code == 200 , updated_tags, None

    return requests.post(
		"https://api.mailgun.net/v3/sandbox6760c092358e462c95ca104e2e4e37dc.mailgun.org/messages",
        auth=("api", "8b7326a77ae25a8c0777b5fa62a65cd0-1553bd45-39c7b91c"),
		data={
		    "from": "SL Python <Joe@sandbox6760c092358e462c95ca104e2e4e37dc.mailgun.org>",
			"to": ["joe@skinlaundry.com"],
			"subject": "Zenoti AR API: Results",
			"text": "The following number of rows will be processed: " +str(current_row)
			}
			            )






def main():

    logger('#### New Zenoti Sync Started ####')
    sheet = initialize()
    global current_row

    current_row = 5
    while (current_row<20000):
        result = sheet.values().get(
            spreadsheetId=SPREADSHEET_ID, range=f'Customer Data2!A{current_row}:G{current_row}').execute()

        values = result.get('values', [])


        if len(values)==0:
            break
        if len(values[0]) == 2:
            status , tags, message = update_zeonti_customer(values[0][0],values[0][1])
            if tags is None:
                pass
            else:
                tags = '|'.join(tags)
            if status:
                status_text = 'Success'
            else:
                status_text = 'Failed'
            result = sheet.values().update(spreadsheetId=SPREADSHEET_ID, range=f'Customer Data2!C{current_row}:E{current_row}',valueInputOption='USER_ENTERED',
                                           body={'values':[[status_text,tags,message]]}).execute()

        time.sleep(1.05)
        current_row+=1


    template_mailing()

if __name__=='__main__':
    main()

name: Push Meta spend into google analytics
text_content:
Issue: We want to know how well meta is performing in booking leads on a cost per lead basis, but Google Analytics has no concept of spend from Meta. 

There are third party tools that hit the APIs of Meta for spend and push data in Google Analytics so we can see performance.

We would like this down to the day grain and AD level - Meta has the spend and Google analytics has Adset/Ad names in a custom dimension called "utm_content" 

Here is an example of how other companies have done it: https://optimoanalytics.com/blog/how-to-import-your-facebook-ads-cost-data-into-google-analytics/

Requirements:
see if we can manually import cost data down to ad level and if not, what level of restructure/changes do we need to do in google analytics
leverage 3rd party or build our own api integration between meta and Google Analytics so it maps cost down to ad level.

name: Integrate Asana to Teams activity notifications
text_content:
Issue: Users in Teams do not know of task CRUD that they are assigned or collaborating on leading to fragmented time/attention.

So as a user of teams, I would like to see changes in Asana that impact me (CRUD) directly or indirectly so I can be more efficient in my work.

What this will likely take:

Webhook from Asana to Teams notifying user of activity (CRUD) on assigned/collaborative tasks
A cross reference of asana user ID's to msft teams id's
Teams activity API: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/graph/teams-send-activityfeednotifications
Asana webhooks: https://developers.asana.com/docs/establish-a-webhook

name: CDN enable these files for new landing Page
text_content:
Put the following files in AWS CDN publicly accessible so that instapage.com can reference for the new landing page they are a building.

Please revert the link for each so we can have them proceed


Due to licensing restrictions, we require that clients provide us with the absolute links for their web fonts that have the font extensions .woff/.ttf/.otf - the only extensions that our builder accepts.
In order to get these absolute links - you will be required to upload the fonts to your company servers or provide direct server links from your third-party font vendor. Please share the links with us using the absolute font path and whitelist them if needed so they can be used in Instapage. Please whitelist our domains (http://www.instapage.com) and (http://www.pagedemo.co) if needed.
An example of an absolute link font path: https://storage.googleapis.com/app-assets/1512500732_helveticaneuemedium.ttf 
Highly recommended - please make sure you have a look at the article from our help center to fully comprehend what this implementation entails. This includes CORs and font whitelisting among other things.

name: Add-on ask
text_content:
Per Client:
"I have another ad hoc request since we are navigating some issues with the launch of our new ecommerce website for b2b. Can I get a quote to add to only the Static Finance Approved dashboard, non-stock item "Shopify - Discount" With our other orders, the discount shows on the product line, but with our ecommerce purchases, the discount shows as this non-stock item. Without this non-stock item, we are showing gross sales, not net after discount."
description:
Per Client:
"I have another ad hoc request since we are navigating some issues with the launch of our new ecommerce website for b2b. name: Adhock Analysis
text_content:
*Goal:* Understanding of NPS by product (Mask v. Core) over time for our Ecommerce customers.

*Method:* Join the customer IDs with the Mask only v. Core customer categorization and break out our NPS scores for each group of customers. 

*Charts*

* Week-over-week line chart of the 2 segments' NPS over time for the past ~3 months of data
* Aggregate NPS for Mask only and Core only for the entire data set
    > including the n breakdown of promoters, neutrals, and detractors (SF, ES any other output you're curious about for this one?)

NPS rules in case you're not familiar - 
If score = 9 or 10, then => "Promoter"
If score = 7 or 8, then => "Neutral"
If score < 7, then => "Detractor"
NPS = % Promoters - % Detractors

Please let me know if you have questions.

name: Estimate for incremental time for full Formsort integration
Formsort Deployment
text_content:
We’ll continue to use the existing intake app for account creation, scheduling, id verification, and payment and we’ll move the questionnaire pieces into Formsort.

See whimsical here, the purple pieces of the flow will live in Formsort. Or see image below...This will require from 

Atidiv/Houndstooth:
Clone the existing intake application
Remove the initial ASRS part 1 quiz section and replace it with an embedded Formsort flow (The ASRS part 1). A dev can embed the Formsort flow into the intake application and will need to pass Formsort the following variables
Healthie ID (as the responder UUID)
The following will be passed in as external variables
First Name
Last Name
Phone Number
Email Address
Once the Formsort flow is completed and it’s determined that the patient should schedule, the intake app will pick up where it left app and continue through scheduling, ID verfication, and payment
Post payment, remove the existing custom “quiz” and embed a formsort flow containing the remainder of the questionnaire.
The intake app will need to pass the Healthie ID (as the responder UUID) into the Formsort app.

We will also need:
Create the calculated variables in Formsort
Upbeat biz team can handle loading in questions and Formsort will handle visuals, but we'll need help with the SQL-derived calculated variables 
An estimate for how long it would take to do a full deployment in Formsort; this is P2

BUG - Ascend and Callrail schema tables swap
text_content:
Tables in callrail and ascend schema were found in both of the schemas. 
It was found that these tables were created on 24th and 25th November, 2022, which is when ascend incremental run began.

The issue occurred because both the jobs were running concurrently at 9:15, 18:15 UTC, and both of them created target bigquery_config.json file in the same folder.

We edited the code so that target config file names are different for different pipelines.

All table names except "users" were different in these 2 schemas. Therefore we deleted the users table from both and reingested the data again. Then we performed Historical ingestion for Ascend since 1st November, 2022. 

All the extra tables have been removed from both the schemas and pipelines now run fine
